    faq2q: "Does the energy class affect the bank's loan-to-value (LTV) ratio?",
    faq2a: "Increasingly so. ECB guidelines on climate risks (2024) encourage banks to integrate energy performance into collateral valuation. In Luxembourg, the CSSF monitors bank exposure to stranded assets. Some banks already apply an additional haircut of 5 to 10% on properties rated F, G, H, or I when calculating LTV.",
    faq3q: "Is the EPC impact estimate reliable?",
    faq3a: "The coefficients used by Tevaxia are calibrated on actual price differences observed in Luxembourg (Observatoire de l'Habitat 2025) and European studies (ECB, PriceHubble, JRC). The range displayed for each class reflects statistical uncertainty. For a precise estimate, a full valuation report (EVS 2025) integrating all property characteristics remains recommended.",
    faq4q: "Why is class D the reference class?",
    faq4a: "Class D corresponds to the median of the Luxembourg housing stock: it is the most common class in transactions. It serves as the neutral point (0% adjustment) because it represents the energy performance expected by the market. Better-rated properties benefit from a premium, while lower-rated properties suffer a discount.",
    faq5q: "How will the trend evolve in the coming years?",
    faq5a: "All studies converge: the value gap between efficient properties and energy sieves will continue to widen. The transposition of the EPBD Directive in 2026, the progressive ban on fossil boilers, and increasing buyer awareness are accelerating this trend. The ECB projects a potential doubling of the brown discount by 2030 for unrenovated properties.",
